    <!-- FairMemoryScreen -->
    <string name="fair_memory_title">Fair Memory</string>
    <string name="overview">Overview</string>
    <string name="fair_memory_overview">Fair Memory is an Android memory management specification jointly advocated by GSA board members (vivo, Xiaomi, OPPO, Honor). It aims to let apps proactively cooperate with the system to release resources through standardized system broadcasts when memory is tight, thereby improving overall device performance and stability, and reducing the probability of background apps being force-killed.</string>
    <string name="how_it_works">How It Works</string>
    <string name="fair_memory_how_it_works">When system memory resources are tight, the device ROM sends specific broadcast notifications to registered apps. Upon receiving the broadcast, apps can perform corresponding memory optimization operations based on the broadcast type, including releasing non-critical caches, stopping low-priority tasks, saving current state, etc. This proactive approach is smoother than the system directly killing processes, effectively reducing the experience interruption caused by app restarts.</string>
    <string name="broadcast_actions">Monitored Broadcast Actions</string>
    <string name="memory_warning_title">1. Memory Warning</string>
    <string name="memory_warning_desc">Action: itgsa.intent.action.TRIM\nSent when system memory is tight. Upon receiving this, apps should proactively release non-critical memory, such as clearing image caches, stopping non-essential background tasks, triggering garbage collection, etc.</string>
    <string name="app_kill_title">2. App Kill</string>
    <string name="app_kill_desc">Action: itgsa.intent.action.KILL\nSent when the system is about to kill this app. Upon receiving this, apps should save critical state data, release all releasable resources, and prepare for process termination.</string>
    <string name="app_adaptation">App Adaptation</string>
    <string name="fair_memory_adaptation">This app has been adapted to the Fair Memory mechanism according to GSA official documentation:\n\n• Dynamically register broadcast receivers at Application startup with RECEIVER_EXPORTED flag\n• Parse common and extra Bundles from Intent, extracting anomaly type (physical memory/Java heap), memory usage, callback IBinder info\n• TRIM broadcast: differentiated release by notifyType — physical memory anomaly (1000) clears entire chart cache, Java heap anomaly (2000) downsamples to keep latest 500 points; both clear scan results and trigger System.gc(), notify system via IBinder callback within 3 seconds\n• KILL broadcast: notify MainViewModel to save state (heart rate data already persisted via Room database), notify system via IBinder callback within 3 seconds\n• Delegate release logic to MainViewModel via MemoryListener interface (WeakReference) to prevent memory leaks\n• Implement IBinder.DeathRecipient to monitor system service abnormal death\n• Use dedicated HandlerThread for broadcast processing to avoid blocking main thread\n\nBLE heart rate service (BleService) runs as a foreground service and won\'t be interrupted by memory warnings. Status bar resident service and floating window service may be reclaimed by the system under extreme memory pressure; the app will auto-recover on next launch.</string>
    <string name="reference_docs">Reference Documentation</string>
    <string name="oppo_desc">Fair Memory Adaptation Guide</string>
    <string name="vivo_desc">Fair Memory Mechanism Adaptation</string>
    <string name="xiaomi_desc">Fair Memory Adaptation: Developer Documentation</string>

